06293nam a22009375i 9781684480364DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20182019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97816844803647 a10.36019/97816844803642doi  a(DE-B1597)541215  a(OCoLC)1083469732  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPQ6055 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a860.9/928722300aModern Spanish Women as Agents of Change :bEssays in Honor of Maryellen Bieder /ced. by Jennifer Smith. 1aLewisburg, PA : bBucknell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Translations -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. Modern Spanish Women Writers as Activists -- t1. Gender, Race, and Subalternity in the Antislavery Plays of María Rosa Gálvez and Faustina Sáez de Melgar -- t2. Forging Progressive Futures for Spain's Women and People: Sofía Tartilán (Palencia 1829- Madrid 1888) -- t3. Fashion as Feminism: Carmen de Burgos's Ideas on Fashion in Context -- tPART II. Emilia Pardo Bazán as Literary Theorist and Cultural Critic -- t4. Emilia Pardo Bazán's "Apuntes autobiográficos" and "El baile del Querubín": A Theoretical Reexamination -- t5. The Twice- Told and the Unsaid in Emilia Pardo Bazán's "Presentido," "En coche- cama," "Confidencia," and "Madre" -- t6. Emilia Pardo Bazán, Joris- Karl Huysmans, and Stories of Conversion -- t7. "A Most Promising Girl": Gender and Artistic Future in Emilia Pardo Bazán's "La dama joven" -- tPART III. Representations of Female Deviance -- t8. A Woman's Search for a Space of Her Own in Gertrudis Gómez de Avellaneda's Dos mujeres -- t9. Caterina Albert i Paradís: Writing, Solitude, and Woman's Jouissance -- t10. The Obstinate Negativity of Ana Ozores -- t11. Female Masculinity in La Regenta -- tAfterword -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume brings together cutting-edge research on modern Spanish women as writers, activists, and embodiments of cultural change, and simultaneously honors Maryellen Bieder's invaluable scholarly contribution to the field. The essays are innovative in their consideration of lesser-known women writers, focus on women as political activists, and use of post-colonialism, queer theory, and spatial theory to examine the period from the Enlightenment until World War II. The contributors study women as agents and representations of social change in a variety of genres, including short stories, novels, plays, personal letters, and journalistic pieces. Canonical authors such as Emilia Pardo Bazán, Leopoldo Alas "Clarín," and Carmen de Burgos are considered alongside lesser known writers and activists such as María Rosa Gálvez, Sofía Tartilán, and Caterina Albert i Paradís. The critical analyses are situated within their specific socio-historical context, and shed new light on nineteenth- and early twentieth-century Spanish literature, history, and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aSpanish literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aWomen and literaturezSpain. 0aWomenzSpainxSocial conditions. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aArkinstall, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArkinstall, Christine.1 aCarbonell, Neus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarbonell, Neus.1 aDuPont, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuPont, Denise.1 aIbarra, Rogelia Lily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIbarra, Rogelia Lily.1 aJohnson, Roberta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary